TI  - Enrichment planting to restore secondary forests in Central Amazon: A perspective on timber production and carbon sequestration
T2  - FOREST ECOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT
AB  - Active restoration can be a strategy to increase timber production and carbon sequestration in secondary forests. Successful enrichment planting depends on selecting species and silvicultural treatments that result in better survival, growth, and stem and wood quality. We evaluate an enrichment planting experiment conducted in a 19 years old (at planting) secondary forest in the Central Amazon that regenerated after two cutting and burning cycles. The treatments were basal area reduction (six levels of canopy refinement: 0, 20, 40, 60, 80, and 100 %) and understory removal (understory slashing at two levels: understory slashed and control). We evaluated the effects of treatments on the survival, height, diameter, commercial height, stem volume, stem forking, stem tortuosity, wood density, biomass increment, and carbon accumulation, of six commercial tree species nearly five-year-old after planting. Survival, height and diameter increased with canopy refinement and understory slashing. Understory maintenance reduced forking and increased commercial height for some species. Wood density reduced slightly or remained unaffected by treatment intensification. Biomass increment and carbon accumulation also increased with canopy refinement and understory slashing. Some of the commercial tree species achieved high carbon sequestration rates (up to 4.14 Mg of aboveground C ha-1 year-1), exceeding those previously reported for unmanaged secondary forests. We concluded that the silvicultural treatments that promote better survival and growth may not produce optimal stem quality. Commercial tree species can sequester carbon at high rates, and as such, enrichment planting can enhance the carbon sequestration potential of secondary forests.
