TI  - The soil hydrologic response to forest regrowth: a case study from southwestern Amazonia
T2  - HYDROLOGICAL PROCESSES
AB  - As a large and dynamic land-use category, tropical secondary forests may affect climate, soils, and hydrology in a manner different from primary forests or agricultural areas. We investigated the saturated hydraulic conductivity K-sat of a Kandiudult under different land uses in Rondonia, Brazil. We measured K-sat at four depths (12.5, 20, 30 and 50 cm) under (a) primary forest, (b) a former banana-cacao plantation (SF1), and (c) an abandoned pasture (SF2). At 12.5 cm, all three land uses differ significantly (alpha = 0.1), but not at the 20 and 30 cm depths. At 50 cm, K-sat was significantly greater in the former pasture than in other land uses. Lateral subsurface flow is expected during intense rainfall (about 30 times per year) at 30 cm depth in SF1 and at 50 em depth in the forest, whereas the relatively low permeability at shallow 12.5 cm in the SF2 may result not only in lateral subsurface flow, but also saturation overland flow. For modelling purposes, recovering systems seem to have Ksat values distinct from primary forest at shallow depths, whereas at deeper layers (>20 cm) they may be considered similar to forests. Copyright (C) 2002 John Wiley Sons, Ltd.
